// Diag snippet: `(0..<5).filter(keep).collect()` over a lazy `FilterIterator`.
// Expected (TS-built compiler): `kept` is the `i32[]` `[2, 3, 4]`, `kept.len()`
// is 3, the program prints "len=3".
//
// Layer 1 — FIXED. The self-host lower used to emit the WRONG `collect`
// overload body: `build_fn_instance_decl` resolved the body by name+arity
// (`find_fn_decl_by_name`), always returning the first `collect` decl
// (`collect(arr: T[])`, std/iter.vader:51) instead of the resolved
// `collect(it: Iterator<T>)` (:62). The `arr: T[]` body then ran `array.len`
// on the iterator struct → trap "array.len receiver: expected array, got
// struct". Fixed: `find_fn_decl_for_symbol` resolves the body by the overload
// symbol's `defined_at` identity, plus `register_fn_instance_mangle` runs the
// instance mangle through `uniq` so same-name overloads don't collide.
//
// Layer 2 — STILL OPEN (this is what the snippet now reproduces). With the
// correct iterator body emitted, the self-host now traps with
//   "vader vm: virtual.call 'Iterator.next' : no impl for type <N>".
// The erased `filter__i32` instance constructs a `FilterIterator__Any` (the
// `Any`-erased struct), but the Iterator vtable is keyed only on the CONCRETE
// `FilterIterator__i32`, so the erased value finds no `next` impl. Same class
// as the §9 F3 erased-dispatch frontier (primitive-Equals vtable gap): the
// vtable needs an entry for the erased struct type, or `filter` must construct
// the concrete tag. TS emits the concrete `FilterIterator__i32` throughout.
//
// `examples/brainfuck/brainfuck.vader::tokenize_bf` was rewritten to an
// explicit accumulator loop to sidestep both layers.

module "snippet"

import "std/io"
import "std/iter"

keep :: fn(x: i32) -> bool = x > 1

main :: fn() -> i32 {
    kept :: (0..<5).filter(keep).collect()
    println("len=${kept.len()}")
    return 0
}
